reason.tex:
%text Expressing $(a+b)^n$ using $\sum$ will help you think about what the \underline\text{general term} is. Identify the general term and half the battle is won.
Hence, get comfortable with seeing the following expansions expressed using $\sum$
% \begin{tabular}{|c|c|} \hline & \text{Using }\sum \\ \hline (a+b)^n & \sum_{k=0}^n {^n}C_k\cdot a^{n-k}\cdot b^k \\ \hline (a-b)^n & \sum_{k=0}^n {^n}C_k\cdot a^{n-k}\cdot(-1)^k\cdot b^k \\ \hline (1+x)^n & \sum_{k=0}^n {^n}C_k\cdot x^k \\ \hline (1-x)^n & \sum_{k=0}^n {^n}C_k\cdot (-1)^k\cdot x^k \\ \hline \end{tabular}
